  "original_title": "Sri Lanka\u2019s JKH profits soar driven by forex gains as soft-peg collapses",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "Sri Lanka\u2019s JKH profits soar driven by forex gains as soft-peg collapses",
      "author": "",
      "body_lines": [
        "ECONOMYNEXT \u2013 Sri Lanka's John Keells Holdings, which has interests in container terminals, consumer goods, financial services and property reported profits of 11.2 billion rupees in the June 2022 quarter helped by 10.1 billion rupees of exchange gains as a soft-peg with the US dollars collapsed.",
        "JKH reported earnings of 8.14 rupees per share for the quarter up from 1.16 rupees a year ago amid a pandemic.",
        "Group revenues rose 84 percent to 71.5 billion rupees, cost of sales rose 71 percent to 53 billion rupees helping grow gross profits to 13.8 billion rupees.",
        "Sri Lanka\u2019s rupee collapsed from 200 to the US dollar to around 360 to the US dollars after two years of money printed to suppress interest rates.",
        "Sri Lanka built a soft-pegged central bank in 1950 giving the country\u2019s economists to print money to suppress rates, trigger balance of payments deficits, high inflation and social unrest.",
        "The current currency crisis is the worst in the history of the central bank with inflation topping 50 percent in the 12 months to June while interest rates are now around 22 to 30 percent.",
        "The group reported finance income of 14.5 billion rupees including forex gains of 10 billion rupees on its foreign exchange holdings.",
        "Costs were rising and the JKH has raised prices where possible, Chairman Krishan Balenddra said.",
        "\u201cWhile the pricing adjustments on account of the inflationary impacts of the depreciation of the currency have taken place to an extent and could be one-off in the event the currency does not",
        "depreciate any further, the sharp rise in interest rates will place pressure on many businesses",
        "due to pressure on funding working capital requirements, particularly in the context of current supply chain challenges,\u201d Balendra said.",
        "To mitigate the volatility JKH converted short term loans to longer term borrowings at fixed rates and also raised money through convertible debenture.",
        "It had paid down a 100 million dollar bridging finance facility. A 225 million dollar loan taken for the Cinnamon Life projects remained. A recent loan from the International Finance Corporation of 175 million US dollars was also in place.",
        "The firm had forex cash balances including thse a placement of shares with the Asian Development Bank and net of borrowing it made a 10.1 billion rupee forex gain.",
        "JKH said depreciation also boosted the numbers of its its container terminal and bunkering businesses.",
        "JKH has leisure operations in the Maldives. The foreign currency translation of foreign operations was 27 billion rupees.",
        "Eventually domestic fixed asset values would also go up with inflation."
      ],
